        <briefdescription>
<para>\par \b Module Contract\/ \:</para>
<para>\par \b Purpose\/ \:  Define the base Annotation class — the root of the annotation hierarchy for all text-level metadata in the document processing pipeline. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>\par \b Scope\/ \:  Base annotation class with position, value, equality, serialization. \par \b Input\/ \:  Start/end positions, annotation name, value string. \par \b Output\/ \:  Annotation base instances consumed by all annotation subclasses. \par \b Links\/ \:  [EXPORTS(10): Annotation, INHERITS(4): Serializable, USES_API(8): ApiAnnotation] \par \b Invariants\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>start &lt;= end (not enforced but expected by convention)</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>name is a non-empty string unique per annotation type</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>is_mergeable defaults to True \par \b Rationale\/ \:</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para>Q: Why inherit from Serializable? A: All annotations must be convertible to API schemas for HTTP responses. \par \b Changes\/ \:</para>
<para>LAST_CHANGE: [v1.0.0 – Added semantic markup and LDD logging] \par \b Module Map\/ \:</para>
<para>CLASS 10[Base annotation class] =&gt; Annotation METHOD 8[Constructor] =&gt; <bold>init</bold> METHOD 6[Equality check] =&gt; <bold>eq</bold> METHOD 4[String representation] =&gt; <bold>str</bold> METHOD 4[Repr] =&gt; <bold>repr</bold> METHOD 8[API schema conversion] =&gt; to_api_schema \par \b Use Cases\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>[Annotation]: Reader → CreateAnnotation → AnnotationStored</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>[Annotation]: Converter → SerializeToAPI → ApiAnnotationReturned </para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
